passages.text: August 29, 2025 04:00 AM GMT

Into 2H25, our framework for stocks is to look for 1) positive EPS momentum (Legrand, ENR), or 2) exposure to depressed end markets that can recover with interest rate cuts, and where we see consensus as de- risked (Sandvik, Rexel). We remain Underweight Alfa Laval, Kone and Schindler.

Stick or twist? A key debate for the next six months is around sticking to 'thematic' stories, or broadening out into interest rate sensitive cyclical names. We prefer a blended approach. We see EPS upgrades at Legrand and ENR, but also like Sandvik and Rexel's mid- term sales and margin recovery runway. What does the data say? We see greenshoots in Europe, US industrial demand holding up but with some pre- buy risk, and risk of China softening into 2H25. On End markets, 2Q25 saw some softness in Process, consumer, Auto capex, resi construction. Solid backdrop for Data- center, Grid and Mining. Marine is a debate. In a relatively expensive sector (20% premium to MSCI Europe), margin execution remains key. Varied margin execution, like 1H25, will continue into 2H25.

Exhibit 1: Current EV/EBIT (1 yr FWD) vs 10- year averages, and peak and trough. Valuations for most stocks are now above mid- cycle averages. We remain selective in data center exposed names (Legrand and Siemens Energy), and also like certain cyclical names (Sandvik and Rexel).
Source: Datastream, Morgan Stanley Research

Backdrop. Stick or twist? We feel there is a some tension in the sector among investors on the 2H25 stock views. Sector share price dispersion has been relatively wide this year, with some higher quality companies seeing their share

prices materially underperform the European Industrials index (SXNP at \(+17\%\) YTD). These include Atlas Copco \((- 11\%)\) , Schneider \((- 12\%)\) and Alfa Laval \((- 5\%)\) which have all seen year- to- date share price declines. We are finding a tendency in our investor conversations, at least to explore, whether the stage may be set for some of these names to catch up in 2H25. We also think there is a pick- up in investor interest in some of the earlier- cycle end markets ahead of potential interest rate cuts, though with an understandable caution given these may be some of the areas (consumer and US residential) that are most vulnerable to growth slowdowns and earnings disappointments at 3Q25 results. On these end markets, and others, we lay out the key data- points in Exhibit 3 to Exhibit 28.

As we head into 2H25, and particularly 3Q25 results, it appears to use there will remain a narrow group of companies seeing meaningful organic growth. It will remain across the datacenter, grid and power gen exposed names, or those names that have significant backlogs from 2025. There have been moments in both 2024 and 2025, where the early- cycle recovery trade gained momentum, but these have been relatively brief as the European industrial recession proved to be more protracted, and the China recovery never came through. Expectations for a 2H25 recovery have already been pushed to the right into 2026. However, the debate is shifting, and with US interest rate cuts on the horizon, we think there will be an increasing investor willingness to look through the more subdued end market trends in some of these early cyclical verticals as we go through the 3Q and 4Q 2025 results.

Our 2H25 framework for stock selection - our views reflect somewhat more of a 'stick with the winners' approach. We agree with the view of trying to find more depressed end markets that have runway for multi- year recoveries as interest rates start to come down. However, within these end markets, we think it is crucial to stick to companies where consensus is largely de- risked for 2H25. Typically this means some of the higher quality construction exposed names (Legrand and Assa), or companies where there may be an idiosyncratic driver, that makes consensus more defendable. In addition, we would also favour companies where EBITA margins are below peak, and where there is room for clear margin expansion in 2026- 27 as the volume recovery comes through. This makes it easier in our view to underwrite 'above sector average EPS growth' for a company on a 1- 2 year view. On some of the themes, we remain selective in datacenter / powering Al exposure (stay OW on Legrand / Siemens Energy). However, on German Fiscal spend and the related beneficiaries (Rion, Siemens), we think this theme has largely run its course for now (for the next six months) after the year- to- date re- rating. There will inevitably be a gap between the initial re- rating of stocks, and the time it takes for fiscal stimulus to actually show up in accelerating German industrial production. For example, on Siemens it has become harder to justify the same sum- of- the- parts upside compared to earlier in 2025. In particular as Siemens AG is no longer trading at a valuation discount to Siemens Healthineers, or one of its key software peers Dassault Systems.

Stocks. Our key Overweights are relatively unchanged and we largely stick with names where we see positive earnings momentum. In this group we would include Legrand and Siemens Energy (both Overweight). The other set of stocks would be

those with more cyclical exposure, where we see low risk for \(\text {ons}\) , relatively undemanding valuations, and runway for multi- year sales and margin recoveries. In this bucket, we would include Sandvik and Rexel (both Overweight). Sandvik's machining is seeing growth now turning positive \(\text {and}\) it has relatively high European exposure in this division. Its execution in \(\text {th}\) \(\text {ing}\) business also stands out across its mining equipment peer group. We like \(\text {Rexel}\) because it is at trough volumes and we think that US price increases and data center growth suggest 2H25 consensus is largely de- risked. Also, current Rexel consensus for 2028 (6.7%) remains below the company's mid- term margin guidance of \(>7\%\) .

Where is risk reward less favourable? And our key Underweight ratings. We continue to see greater risk of some of the later- cycle Process / Marine exposures decelerating in orders, and we retain an Underweight on Alfa Laval. We also think risk reward remains unappealing at Equal- weight rated Wartsila at current levels. We would also avoid companies with full valuations, which we think will be unable to demonstrate clear accelerations in EPS growth into 2026/27. In this category, we retain Underweight ratings on Kone and Schindler across the Elevator names. We also think that, after the recent re- rating, ABB's (Equal- weight) valuation again looks full, even if the underlying business continues to perform relatively well. ABB's valuation is only now trading at a - 5% discount to Legrand and Schneider, despite relatively slower EPS growth in 2026- 27, in our view. Finally, we think risk reward on Prysmian (Equal- weight) is skewed to the downside here. We appreciate that Prysmian will likely upgrade FY25 guidance, which keeps the short- term momentum, but there are risks of slowing High Voltage orders into 2026. Also, 2028 EBITDA consensus (€3.12bn) is again near the upper end of the company's guidance range (€2.95bn- €3.15bn), which effectively is embedding relatively flawless execution as a requirement across the respective businesses.

Back to school: What the data say: European greenshoots, US moving sideways (but with risks), some signs of China softening. We are leaning more towards EU Industrial and Construction exposure for 2H25, while seeking to broadly avoid China exposure.

(1) Signs of European greenshoots. European Industrial Production has been slightly positive in 1H25, growing at 1.4%, and now at a similar rate to US industrial production. In terms of greenshoots, we would highlight the pick-up in the German IFO business expectations (Exhibit 6), the improved Japan machine tool orders into Europe (Exhibit 3), and residential construction permits (Exhibit 7) where France in particular has been an important driver (Exhibit 8). Much of this is driven by easing comparators, rather than any material 2H25 improvement, but nonetheless the easing comp effect should allow more European cyclically exposed names to see a stabilization or even growth in 2H25. If we take a simple example like Auto production by region in Exhibit 24, we can see Europe is still well below 2019 levels, and EU Auto sales (+5.9% in July) are growing. Our more constructive Europe comments are as much about the low base and the easy comparators, rather than any significant structural bull case on mid-term European manufacturing.

(2) The US is a mixed picture. Softer US data like the July ISM have been relatively weak. Within the overall index (48 in July) the new orders (47.1) and employment (43.4) components were not encouraging for the overall economy. Similarly, we

have written in our recent report, Pre- buy; Another risk for Industrials, that inventories across US distributors and US Cap Goods companies have ticked up, indicating some element of pre- buy has likely occurred (see Exhibit 12). That said, when we look at the hard data like Fastenal monthly sales (Exhibit 10), US Durable goods orders (Exhibit 11), and Industrial loans (Exhibit 16), we are not seeing any clear softening in the July data. In construction, data has clearly been more mixed with the US non- residential put in place construction YOY growth negative for most of 2025 (Exhibit 14), Dodge manufacturing construction starts (Sq feet) firmly back in decline in July (Exhibit 15) and the residential construction data remaining choppy. Even if there were some US residential construction starts in July (Exhibit 13), the US residential permits are still painting a much more subdued picture.

(3) China. A solid 1H25, but risks are building for 2H25. We would argue there are some emerging signs of a slowdown in China. The recent PMI data has been more subdued and China Fixed asset investment (Exhibit 17) also dipped in the latest reading. This is against a backdrop of an increased focus on China Anti-involution (see our recent report) and on-going total social financing data which is not growing YOY on a rolling 12mths basis (Exhibit 21). In terms of other data, a more constructive data point was China Automation company Innovance showed accelerating July orders (+20%), but it remains difficult to disaggregate their growth between underlying market activity and market share gains. Similarly, Airtac's July sales were -2% MOM/+7% YOY in July, which MS analyst Derrick Yang suggested means company revenue is running slightly behind market expectations (Link to report). Ultimately, there is not conclusive evidence of a clear slowdown, but we think this region is one with relatively higher risk compared to Europe / US in the next six months.

(4) Broader end market capex trends. We find that current capex expectations for most industries are holding up relatively well in 2025, and we have not seen widespread capex push-outs. In terms of project deferrals, these have come more in some of the US clean energy projects, and also Automation companies citing some hesitation across Automotive customers. However, when we look at our capex tracker, we see aggregate capex for 2026 is slightly down YOY (Exhibit 22), with weaker spending forecast in Pharma, Chemicals and Semis YOY in 2026e. When we look at Marine markets (Exhibit 26 and Exhibit 27), new ship ordering data has stayed weak in July, and we remain below consensus on Alfa Laval and Wartsila Marine orders into 2025. Then, on mining capex, we see scope for this to accelerate into 2026/27 given continued strong commodity prices (Exhibit 28) and also given signs of increased Copper project sanctioning in 2025 (Exhibit 28).

**Exhibit 2:** European and US Industrial Production recovering. US Industrial Production increased +1.43% YoY in July 25 vs +0.8% YoY in June. Since February 25, European IP has shown signs of recovery following 2 years of Industrial Recession. In June EU IP was +0.5% YoY and +2.9% YoY in May.
Source: Refinitiv, Morgan Stanley

Exhibit 3: Asia Machine Tool Orders YoY decelerating in China and US, whilst Europe is past the trough. China orders have decelerated YoY in June and July (+2%, +8% respectively) from \(\sim 40\%\) YoY 12month average (May 24- 25), albeit against tough comparators. Similarly, US orders were +4% YoY in July vs 17% in June and 23% in May. On the other hand, Europe accelerated +12% YoY in July, marking the first month of positive order growth since December 2023 (+1% YoY).
Source: JMBTA, Morgan Stanley Research

Exhibit 4: Global Manufacturing PMIs. These are still below 50 across all regions, and the July reading was slightly behind consensus in US and China. European July figures showed the slowest contraction since July 2022. European August Flash Manufacturing PMI crossed the 50 mark at 50.5, suggesting this upturn can slowly gather pace into 2H.
Source: Haver, Morgan Stanley Research.

Exhibit 5: European and US consumer confidence. In the US, consumer confidence has bounced back from the lows, but has still been damaged by the tariffs discussions. In the Euro Area, August consumer confidence has eased from a recent uptick in the last 4 months.
Source: Refinitiv, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 6: German IFO is improving. We are still at relatively low levels, but business expectations are gradually improving in August to 91.6 from 90.8 in July, despite the concerns on tariffs.
Source: Haver, Morgan Stanley Research.

Exhibit 7: European Construction – Permits have had a stop-start YTD but most recent data are encouraging. April resi permits increased double digit vs last year (+11% YoY) and non- resi accelerated 2% MoM. On a YoY basis, non- resi permits still declined by 3% but this marks an improvement from the - 11% YoY drop in March.
Source: Haver, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 8: French and German Resi construction permits are still at relatively low levels but seem to be past the worst. France is now growing YOY.
Source: Haver, Morgan Stanley Research

Exhibit 9: US ISM New Orders vs US Philadelphia FED. The US ISM has lacked direction in recent months, with uncertainty around tariffs remaining an overhang. New orders and the broader ISM remain below 50.
Source: Datastream, Morgan Stanley Research

**Exhibit 10:** US Distributor Fastenal saw its July sales growth accelerate to 12.8% in July, from 9.8% in June and 9.3% in May. Price was likely the bigger driver of the acceleration, but nonetheless it is a solid print and suggests that US Industrial volumes remain solid.
Source: Company Data, Morgan Stanley Research
**Exhibit 11:** US Durable goods orders are holding up. They increased 4% YoY in July following a 2% increase in June.
Source: Haver, Morgan Stanley Research.

Exhibit 12: Rolling 12mths Inventory to sales. We see an uptick in inventories of US Distributors, and also US Cap Goods companies. We see some evidence of a US pre-buy. US inventory / sales are now back to levels seen coming out of COVID when we heard a number of companies talking about keeping 'safety stock'.
12 Months Rolling Inventory to Sales

Source: Company Data, Morgan Stanley Research. US distributors = Fastenal, WW Grainger, Wesco. EU Cap Goods = Legrand, Schneider, Sandvik, Epiroc, Atlas, Alfa Laval. US Cap Goods = Eaton, Emerson, Vertiv, 3M, Hubbell, Ingersoll Rand, Trane Technologies.
Exhibit 13: US residential housing starts accelerated in July whilst permits are lagging behind. We look to see whether this pick- up in starts is sustainable, given the lack of inflexion in permits.
Source: US Census Bureau, Morgan Stanley Research

Exhibit 14: US non-residential construction spend (\$) has been in a modest decline for most of 2025. This differs across verticals with areas like Datacenter remaining strong, but most other segments in decline.
Source: Haver, Morgan Stanley Research

Exhibit 15: Rolling 6mths Dodge manufacturing construction starts. These are less negative and, while we expect a recovery in US capex investment in the midterm, in the next 6- 12mths we may continue to see some hesitancy from corporates as higher prices from tariffs are digested into the economy.
Source: Haver, Morgan Stanley Research

**Exhibit 16:** US Commercial and Industrial Loans. These have returned to positive growth in the last few months, suggesting some easing of loan activity. This has not yet shown up in any meaningful acceleration in the broader industrial economy.
Source: Haver, Morgan Stanley Research
**Exhibit 17:** YoY % YTD China Fixed Asset Investment - Manufacturing. This slowed in July, and raises questions around the trajectory of China industrial activity into 2H25.
Source: Haver, Morgan Stanley Research

Exhibit 18: Inovance Monthly Order growth. This accelerated into July, which was a more positive China data-point. It is unclear in this data how much of the order growth can be attributed to market share gains versus underlying demand accelerating.
Source: Company Data, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 19: Hiwin / Airtac monthly sales. Slightly down MoM for Airtac but still growing YOY in July.
Source: Company Data, Morgan Stanley Research

Exhibit 20: Semis sales. These have been volatile, but grew 7% MoM in June, below the normal seasonal \(12.9\%\) M/M increase. The YOY growth (below chart) was \(+18\%\) . This was a broadly in- line result, which showed relatively limited impact from tariffs.
Source: SIA, Morgan Stanley Research

Exhibit 21: China Social Financing. On a 12mths rolling basis this is not growing at a time when the China PMI remains slightly below 50 and industrial activity is relatively sluggish. We think the broader theme of China anti- involution is also unhelpful for China- related demand for our Cap Goods companies.
Source: Haver, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 22: MS Capex Tracker (US\(mn). Capex flattening out in 2026.
Source: Company Data, Factset, Visible Alpha, Morgan Stanley Research

Exhibit 23: 2025 Global Capex is set to increase across most end markets in 2025 with the exception of Oil & Gas. However, most end markets are set to decelerate YoY in 2026. Chemicals and Pharma are expected to have the largest deceleration.
Source: Company Data, Morgan Stanley Research

Exhibit 24: Global Auto Production is still expected to be below 2018 levels in the mid- term. Regionally, the expected decrease in Autos Production in North America and Europe in 2025e and 2026e is offset by South America and Asia.
Source: IHS Markit, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 25: Airbus and Boeing Deliveries. Airbus back to 2019 levels in 2026. We think an ongoing A&D and Auto recovery can help Sandvik's machining division.
Source: Company Data, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 26: Ship orders (3MMA). This has taken a sharp step down yoy, rolling over from four strong years of ship ordering in 2021- 24.
Source: Clarkson Data, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 27: YTD Ship Orders declines by segment. Total ship orders have decreased 60% YTD driven by Tankers and Gas Carriers.
Source: Clarkson Data, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 28: Sandvik SMR Orders vs Commodity Price Index. The commodity price backdrop remains healthy in 2025 and Sandvik continues to deliver faster order growth compared to its peers.
Source: Company Data, Datastream, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 29: Relative MS organic growth (yoy%) forecasts for 2026 vs 2025. We see accelerations at many of the mechanicals names into 2026.
Source: Morgan Stanley Research

Exhibit 30: Sector Re/De-rating from Liberation Day (2nd April 2025). The re-rating has been most notable across thematic names in Power Gen, German Fiscal Beneficiaries, or Data center. We can continue to justify names that have re-rated by the continued potential upgrades to consensus (Legrand and ENR). However, we see value in names like Sandvik, Rexel and Spirax.
Source: Visible Alpha, Datastream, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 31: Legrand's share price has rallied the most since the US liberation day announcement. Atlas, Schneider and Alfa have struggled.
Source: Datastream, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 32: Examining the data moves month by month
